            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Cody Tanaka\u2019s name is a story in itself. Born to young, white parents in Daly City, his early life was marked by instability. The surname, the one he carries with pride, came from Kenji Tanaka, the gentle man who married his mother when Cody was seven. Kenji, a third-generation Japanese American gardener, provided the stability and kindness Cody\u2019s biological father never could. He wasn\u2019t a man of many words, but he taught Cody the value of quiet patience and tending to things that needed care.\n\nThe defining moment of Cody\u2019s life arrived not in a classroom, but at home with the birth of his half-sister, Maya. Born with a severe developmental disability, Maya required constant, specialized attention. While others saw a burden, teenage Cody saw a purpose. He discovered a deep, innate talent for connecting with her, for understanding her non-verbal cues, and for patiently helping her navigate a world not built for her. He barely scraped by to get his high school diploma, as his focus was on Maya and supporting his mother. College was never a realistic option.\n\nAfter Kenji passed away from a sudden illness, the family was adrift. Cody, then 21, stepped up. He earned his certification as a Direct Support Professional and found a job at a center specializing in care for adults with disabilities. When a position opened at a renowned facility in San Francisco, they made the move, finding a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond.\n\nNow 28, Cody\u2019s life revolves around a simple, demanding rhythm. His day begins before sunrise, catching the 38 Geary for the 3.5-mile commute to his job. There, he provides essential support\u2014from personal care to vocational training\u2014with a calm resolve that his colleagues admire. His $52,000 salary is stretched thin in the city, shared with his mother's social security income. Social life is a luxury, mostly consisting of a weekly beer with a coworker or quiet evenings at home.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco isn\u2019t about its glamour, but its services. He loves the city for Golden Gate Park, where he takes Maya on weekends, and for the resources it provides her. His dream isn\u2019t of wealth or status, but of stability. He hopes to one day afford a small, ground-floor condo somewhere quiet, a permanent, accessible home for Maya, ensuring the legacy of care his stepfather taught him will always have a place to flourish."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, standing in the fog-dampened soil of their Daly City backyard. Kenji was showing him how to stake a young tomato plant. \u201cBe gentle,\u201d his stepfather said, his voice quiet as the mist. \u201cIt needs support to grow straight.\u201d Cody carefully tied the twine, realizing Kenji wasn\u2019t just talking about the plant. In that moment, he understood that providing quiet, steady support was a form of love. It was the single most important lesson he would ever learn, the foundation of the man he was becoming.\n\n2.\nMaya was fifteen, and her world had collapsed into a storm of guttural, frustrated sounds. His mother was near tears, helpless. Cody ignored the noise, knelt beside his sister's chair, and began humming a simple, tuneless melody he\u2019d made up for her years ago. Her thrashing slowly stilled. She turned her head and met his eyes, a flicker of recognition and calm. In that instant, his purpose crystalized. He wasn\u2019t just her brother; he was her translator, her anchor. He had a calling.\n\n3.\nThe first time he unlocked the door to the Inner Richmond apartment, he was twenty-two. The air was thick with the smell of old paint and the faint promise of a new start. It was small, the floors creaked, and the view was a brick wall. But as he helped Maya navigate her wheelchair over the threshold, he felt a profound sense of relief. This wasn't a choice for himself, but for her\u2014a safe, ground-floor space in a city of services. This was his promise to Kenji made real.\n\n4.\nLast Sunday in Golden Gate Park, he pushed Maya\u2019s wheelchair along a path near the Dutch windmills. A breeze rustled the cypress trees, and Maya pointed at a monarch butterfly, a rare, bright smile spreading across her face. Looking at her simple joy against the backdrop of the city, Cody felt a wave of pure contentment. This was why he endured the 38 Geary, the tight budget, the exhaustion. This simple, free, beautiful moment was his version of success. It was all the richness he needed.\n\n5.\nA few months ago at work, a client was having a severe, non-verbal panic attack. While others raised their voices, Cody simply sat near him, methodically organizing a set of colored blocks on a table. The client\u2019s breathing slowly matched the calm, repetitive motion. Afterward, a coworker Cody respected just said, \u201cMan, you have a gift.\u201d He felt a quiet pride, not in being special, but in knowing that the difficult language of love he learned with Maya had a universal power to heal."
